  "entries": {
    "ballad:A leaf turns sunlight into fuel. Where inside it does that very first step happen?": "4aa12cebfccde2776f054d5d5684e444d938c678dc391f0b6d2ac9e7a90bd807.mp3",
    "ballad:ATP + NADPH → carbon fixation.": "0d0b5e87366e3ff462e15bbb28c2b9d607ffcc34c5c6935ad61f9f3c74adea74.mp3",
    "ballad:ATP and NADPH from the light reactions provide energy and energized electrons for carbon fixation.": "fd9f8fbac7750793481ce83e959b78df278fa45f923684a83bef12b60a9f6bc1.mp3",
    "ballad:ATP and NADPH support carbon fixation; oxygen is not their cargo and water is not their product.": "511daabd9fef0a924de560652de09909998e79464b0c7e99fa1fe01c76fdd523.mp3",
    "ballad:Catching light is only the beginning. What does the plant make first, before any sugar?": "546e757ef4f544e9f9ce8e1c008bc4280d0d31b71f886896e00d09f7d21ba345.mp3",
    "ballad:Check the cargo heading for the next stage.": "0d69de0507ff660a2f3c0f77dc515fffe6191a83921c15104d2bacb85845dcd6.mp3",
    "ballad:During light reactions, water is split to replace electrons and releases oxygen.": "9f14ba8e3d9f16a35c5baa515aced91fc319ad28a7534dbc388de37f029ec165.mp3",
    "ballad:Explorer's call — find where the light gets caught.": "c2c13691678130a56a06e1e49791197bdd21930ff76b1462b594220cc286bdb1.mp3",
    "ballad:Good instinct, explorer. ATP and NADPH carry the energy and reducing power that support building carbon compounds in the Calvin cycle.": "e447261c320457bbe4a985d1ff6086c4e68c4d3ce9f0cee6091b7bfd40dd49d4.mp3",
    "ballad:Good instinct, explorer. ATP supplies usable energy and NADPH carries energized electrons to support carbon fixation; oxygen is a by-product.": "68dee01499889fe4602415a1a8151439d3c889f0112f90b55d6bc86b63c6370a.mp3",
    "ballad:Good instinct, explorer. In thylakoids, light reactions split water, release oxygen, and produce ATP and NADPH for later carbon fixation.": "5a70fe3a9d9b24dd32d037281aa8b98e24dd12078d451a974aac78331ebb0629.mp3",
    "ballad:Good instinct, explorer. Light reactions occur in thylakoid membranes. A cell wall is outside the cell, and the nucleus stores DNA.": "c6075ee61ad92898098f4ccc56c2bbb5fab0ca97c16a253acef6881986781f4c.mp3",
    "ballad:Good instinct, explorer. Water splitting supplies electrons and releases oxygen. Carbon dioxide is used later to build carbon compounds.": "a9051bc90e48374d07ef88a8365b4527f75e3542317a44e8ec23127a96f72044.mp3",
    "ballad:Here's where it all clicks into place.": "25cbaac1d06df15ee3cb7a81f86556d4787ab181ca09c1b6d096e0a26f361b3c.mp3",
    "ballad:H₂O → electrons + O₂.": "468bc03c3aad884ad94eff6101db16224194babca0fa0f0fcbc9a17027a528c1.mp3",
    "ballad:LIGHT REACTIONS → thylakoids.": "d6e45af88fb65b83f9cc0c538643b8bd11e7ef23a901f76453041d3b602d55e0.mp3",
    "ballad:Last one — the whole picture in a single answer.": "1de5aa451135d9d20e30ca3be707c118db7df377f46cf8213962dbe8c5898909.mp3",
    "ballad:Light reactions happen in thylakoids, not in the cell wall or nucleus.": "d2e7e7767a1681d32a6b916cfe4a04ea5b9b511148e15691dff73d157ba4b98b.mp3",
    "ballad:Next: Sugar-Building Beyond the Storm.": "9a15685019555f151a5346788748bec905b22bf365f408612ae8f2b9e12ed9ed.mp3",
    "ballad:Quest briefing: sunlight just struck the leaf. Somewhere inside, the first step begins — let's find the room.": "8e5820723b1157750a188e376f68bf5cd0944af88754559eb42873a4429e2185.mp3",
    "ballad:The light reactions use light in thylakoid membranes inside chloroplasts.": "25550a8151077969342b2a1d27fe5dacf5c53d943f472090b76dfd077ecd95da.mp3",
    "ballad:The light stage packed some supplies for the road ahead. Let's see what it's carrying.": "a04c40fce45be4722a32f034c4edae09d86c9d7f57cbd1383d933931aded2512.mp3",
    "ballad:The oxygen in your next breath came from a plant tearing something apart. What?": "47ab25c4b6729ce9613fde0d603cfdbc658988b4f1e9f5fe37d8cd9be53f9eaa.mp3",
    "ballad:The oxygen in your next breath starts here, with the plant taking something apart. Let's see what.": "d88110e3df0f33178563e13078445b03e072e3774d61adc58fb1911990b845de.mp3",
    "ballad:They are charged delivery packs carried from the solar-panel room to the sugar-building workshop.": "899cbeda57f580f1e2505d5ce089c9df768894a538e36c89a6c2d1c364ffec57.mp3",
    "ballad:Thylakoids are solar-panel rooms where chlorophyll catches light energy.": "d306a7ea24e603fe60ca34c22136db1d5420ec2fa08b0e718dcf9faf9483a534.mp3",
    "ballad:Trace the split and name what's set loose.": "dab21841bc42a62924fb42c9137dff958d03079ce41dbefeab54f8963f79a939.mp3",
    "ballad:Water is a supply crate: its electrons keep the light system running while oxygen exits as a by-product.": "2b412c1a0ad4f9e3f7ebf34044e1352a2dace7d814f5eeeaedd370cea077fc27.mp3",
    "ballad:Water splitting releases oxygen; carbon dioxide is used later to build carbon compounds.": "fa11996f8a36bbdb40614afa14d24282be5e6ad9bbe0c566c92768e174787e4d.mp3",
    "cedar:A narrow hallway slows a crowd; more resistance leaves less current for the same push.": "57e72a60401df3efa9076bd6a4c41d997ba3d257c61004943c68539f229995a0.mp3",
    "cedar:CURRENT = flow of charge.": "68928a11da5d76253d8d24ecd267e7617356add6f87fe7a1acb90ef919e92bd5.mp3",
    "cedar:Close read, cadet. Current is moving electric charge. Voltage pushes, while resistance opposes that flow.": "2e673e6e46c7856aa19da6776a218304cc0243ac952bd0774d15c156d87dc9d1.mp3",
    "cedar:Close read, cadet. I = V/R, so 24 volts divided by 6 ohms equals 4 amperes.": "ed6fa5b0039ecf9a1f2a738609eee7fe0fd67189c2b6f88b7be03eef41036713.mp3",
    "cedar:Close read, cadet. Increasing resistance lowers current when voltage is fixed. Raising voltage increases current; opening the path stops the circuit rather than tuning it.": "93fb28e84d8b128617569717548f719036773ec7df1e067c70a4c4ce644ed9d7.mp3",
    "cedar:Close read, cadet. Ohm's law is I = V/R, so increasing resistance at fixed voltage lowers current.": "d9bf25bcc90e9ee7daa0672dc7f96842c6e6f7c57eac8ee0592b4802546b3a00.mp3",
    "cedar:Close read, cadet. Voltage is the electrical push; current describes how much charge flows, and a component does not automatically supply a push.": "2597fc315289cfca4ea3cd84d653e9258e2f8bbab7aacc4792118c20e5f919cd.mp3",
    "cedar:Current is the flow; voltage supplies the push and resistance makes flow harder.": "eb770a7ba7b6bbaa69f56f7da0fc8f85be92727bc57e846f6502e84b35105add.mp3",
    "cedar:Electric current is the movement of electric charge through a complete path.": "0891ba37f516cd9b652f29eb953b9061820d6ffe8934dc551b4e7e3d6a5467d3.mp3",
    "cedar:Engineers predict a circuit's current before they ever build it. Here's the rule that lets them.": "1024f016276a3321b0499403fec0c1d717504bef61a66b033938786b664a2c45.mp3",
    "cedar:Flip a switch and something starts moving through the wire almost instantly. What is it?": "e72485c7475c6c38175821bd6879c88d7fd2795d0fc611ab0b1301714216001a.mp3",
    "cedar:For a circuit calculation, start with Ohm's law: current equals voltage divided by resistance.": "93ce3850b8627c373b763567a05ca6b163d9d3b0660bd23ed39bf90ffdbb2324.mp3",
    "cedar:I = V ÷ R.": "7e949e743b2334722d0bb1de4a33e35165278ceffe0bb9437e548e26530e8e46.mp3",
    "cedar:If voltage is the hill, current is the stream of balls rolling down it each second.": "83be0614c6eabad945d5f9daed84c4c5dcdb2def9be9934cd380d9b98bf9af3f.mp3",
    "cedar:Instruments ready — call the current before we build it.": "1f43f892a6c8609c1a7758ccc414bbcbac9b59a8c11e00d000594fcca0da077a.mp3",
    "cedar:Last one — the whole picture in a single answer.": "84d264e924425df4b25aada6baa47ae175bf43a8c57ff9b36bf905a774efce22.mp3",
    "cedar:Meter's live — read what's actually moving through the loop.": "c0222e7d462f5886d7f4d760d2be743d126582ec75af46908ea09904dc4023fa.mp3",
    "cedar:More resistance does not create current. At fixed voltage, it lowers current.": "c9837ca342df7cbaa6aa46d78f9105ce6d927a16a8ce962b662d5aff81268655.mp3",
    "cedar:Name the units as you work: volts are the push, ohms resist flow, and amps measure current.": "ffb40400f9dd2141a13e9da876f7756e768f73f6ed33ed1a3c43970b9f0271dc.mp3",
    "cedar:New tool — turn what you already know into a quick calculation.": "16b6354afa6061d00b60f4eb9f55be5394c67b02219d9cf7e728000c22eb8b7c.mp3",
    "cedar:Next: Resistance Riddles in the Outer Circuit.": "71064a8ea5b5b7e2eee9901ad20bd7ae4494c298489798817183f4b64d80bfec.mp3",
    "cedar:Ohm's law links current, voltage, and resistance: current equals voltage divided by resistance.": "6f0e21c887fc6d4796b664dedc78bc3999cb2bad89897ac6339019ff9e6f99e8.mp3",
    "cedar:Power is moving through the wires now — but moving how, and how much? Next reading, please.": "cd9b2ac730dbe23daaa7f24cde7d893aa7941565e790c4e7be5c6bba31347253.mp3",
    "cedar:Signal from the frontier: the ship's circuit is alive with something we can't see. Time to name it.": "a67be1e6374c72b650cec0f35540459bf2eddda428a1a91be0b4c473989f76cd.mp3",
    "cedar:Signal's yours now, cadet — lock in what voltage really is.": "c78adfe30dfa3f379504fcc6fdccd027fc35080b35b21f2387fff2cdf3e20889.mp3",
    "cedar:The crew wants to predict this circuit before they ever flip the switch. Let's find the rule.": "0d102c09608b3760091f7337d23b602b85491d0b9319565458c5eeeea994a763.mp3",
    "cedar:Think of a water tower: higher water presses harder through a hose, like voltage pushes charge.": "6cbc4b12a73908365e54f4de322a25e2aebaed4c532e01697c041bc9e5546cc3.mp3",
    "cedar:VOLTAGE = push on charge.": "11c8bbc4a6f8ec33517db57a84af8d0f2430a1724b671e3d8124f890beeef91e.mp3",
    "cedar:Voltage is an energy difference that pushes electric charge through a complete circuit.": "e06e572886788e02bb6c139d1a038dc4a927bccb30e6af6f441001be5655c018.mp3",
    "cedar:Voltage is the push, not the moving charge. Moving charge is current.": "ef025d68fb30c82c2c4d2671fb9d7012e50f80411951418cb56e434107c98621.mp3",
    "cedar:Worked example: 12 volts through 6 ohms means I equals 12 divided by 6, so 2 amps flow.": "e0f172998ff2da5b7f56bc107c8f50e63caaaa9961c023be018437df6881f0c3.mp3",
    "cedar:Your phone charger and a lightning bolt rely on the same hidden push. Let's name it.": "0af4d77d0e9bf414bffcd8c2a5dc53bd23906726ddcfaf88b90d1fb3a562ec6f.mp3",
    "cedar:Your turn — run the numbers.": "00991199be55b38924554c01c2905d91cdba1295340785a31462a43d3de43294.mp3",
    "marin:A hockey puck glides across smooth ice and just keeps going. What would it take to change that?": "b39c8ff5dfd00805652c70447d2e6c73e610af5a4464e00496782c92d8fce38e.mp3",
    "marin:A rocket in empty space has nothing to push against, yet it still flies. How?": "79e74da33633d9b2dc4f707da8ce595779c42eb26416f2622263850686e20fae.mp3",
    "marin:A tug-of-war stays still when both teams pull equally; motion changes when one side wins.": "47a0cb65588b6eebaf761dac323f7ee21596273543f3912f61c760628f3a12cf.mp3",
    "marin:ACTION ↔ REACTION (two objects).": "d60c66a6b7b01a1e20e03d2ce250371482d4257055e24684eb32a7579c3f9a01.mp3",
    "marin:An object's motion changes only when forces are unbalanced, creating a nonzero net force.": "afc0283b4abb9838d6177c62a21f3baa7ce34b8918fd2d2563b8c6eb85c8062a.mp3",
    "marin:Balanced does not mean no forces. It means the forces cancel.": "0e575662811b674aa089b170211859b95b2e574a48579318f9d56f6bea086d8c.mp3",
    "marin:Call it, squad — what changes an object's motion?": "68df9fb33f0df02bfa8e8214954f9ad74da85135225aac0c9bf8aed1ef7a0d28.mp3",
    "marin:Every hero move comes with a partner reaction. Let's spot the pair.": "4109654cc9dbd5c06dd80b10a11d9a5d7cd75174014c2a99a20f0bf8d16f3d6b.mp3",
    "marin:F = m × a.": "4f7304c4f9ee5585dd326d32a53c7a1a4e8e85bf8ffed3dd3c85497a93704bf2.mp3",
    "marin:For every force on one object, there is an equal and opposite force on another object.": "05b180da50cb390c70841eb87969909b92d7e6931b380da30a14d3cc6dc537e5.mp3",
    "marin:For force problems, rearrange Newton's second law: acceleration equals net force divided by mass.": "b94b736f8bd5b684b9df4fd7fbae607297ecf95f4735f511b6c91f389f5d93a6.mp3",
    "marin:Good effort, squad. A net force causes acceleration, and the ground and wheels exert an equal-and-opposite pair on different objects.": "fbd3d61309d6d96ef812c6995eefd1a84256067e6766d60056fa1623ea83b61c.mp3",
    "marin:Good effort, squad. Balanced forces cancel, so a net (unbalanced) force is needed to change motion.": "1714fa66cb1af39253d558f8cd92baa59b5741a5d0dc8e847bd3b4ae08778d5e.mp3",
    "marin:Good effort, squad. Newton's second law says acceleration increases when net force increases for the same mass.": "cce6c672ebfd2f2dba8dfa23b6ba2cbb5339c70da9c239eaf3bcd74e8177d9c0.mp3",
    "marin:Good effort, squad. Newton's third-law forces are equal and opposite on different objects, so exhaust pushes the rocket forward.": "33a0cc6ad69d2efe3754039195172b8e13d8bd5ca90fe716cc066670cb4cc6d5.mp3",
    "marin:Good effort, squad. Using F = ma, acceleration is 8 newtons divided by 2 kilograms: 4 m/s².": "83f443453f984c82cd569dcffe3a8f7f0ffc2f766fb9aff28b0ec0a626dd2b80.mp3",
    "marin:Hero training, lesson one: things in motion have a mind of their own. What does it take to change that?": "bb2b594b901431da2d95054345b38400470cdfbc7a75a11c1e2c71d958387c75.mp3",
    "marin:Last one — the whole picture in a single answer.": "164b24148aa88e263889b8f2f711fbaeeb1cf152e25e788ff8cf79772328fc66.mp3",
    "marin:More force gives more acceleration only when mass stays the same.": "285e4328adb49c3c563934f7081b519f050078e535c9fe2f214116185046186d.mp3",
    "marin:NET FORCE 0 → no motion change.": "ffcf1f105370acbc1c260060a7c23d9ecb93de954b77ddaa29105f34d1d3106a.mp3",
    "marin:New tool — turn what you already know into a quick calculation.": "270c2884aab93932bee07243156bf87dbea087b4e87dde8476406b29ba87ccfa.mp3",
    "marin:Newton's second law says net force causes acceleration, and F equals mass times acceleration.": "6588ae7a46b163b140aae8bbc114a86215a6ba2824ad110851c16e34284c401e.mp3",
    "marin:Next: Friction vs. the Rolling Rover.": "f6dce91858d0d895ff669524214d12436a0797f8d049dd4e26aa140e29f81eb5.mp3",
    "marin:Power meter's yours — make the read on that push.": "12f5f75e30c263663e2d8d46cfdbcf5bba286501292332e1b42917a44bc048ad.mp3",
    "marin:Same shove, wildly different results. Squad, we need the rule that explains it.": "e5aed3e4af75123541d79c19bad171689a59e98f2716ed9d2737aa63c5b4b278.mp3",
    "marin:Team-up time — spot the partner force.": "95b16bdfbe326d52cb906c6e6a59a2e5c2aae0a53e64290ba8498b4aa38b9ecd.mp3",
    "marin:The pair is equal but acts on two different objects, so it does not cancel on one object.": "174e91c93d2bc8c0c1dd76f391bd37bb6dfefe2101fe5e58af37168c669a4068.mp3",
    "marin:The same push changes a shopping cart more than a heavy truck because the truck has more mass.": "9cc28d3c1bc89d619879149a6a21a3e881962c7cf1e30b1b88bf242b2e05c0e1.mp3",
    "marin:The same shove barely moves a truck but launches a light cart. Why the difference?": "e6751f71cb23f50e8ed78d23150f394354c4d5ecc2a6d9e7af5d63720a8cf949.mp3",
    "marin:Use net force, not just any single push, because net force is what changes the cart's motion.": "5af6be24ee503e242131a4599a120c19763f89cf1ec97fa6b944a5b97c85a779.mp3",
    "marin:When you step off a skateboard, your foot pushes it back while it pushes you forward.": "d70c88db7c5536dfa0f95c58cbe0a77f6991bc41e6dc8d6ebef0f2fee1bce064.mp3",
    "marin:Worked example: a 6-newton net force on a 2-kilogram cart gives 6 divided by 2, or 3 meters per second squared.": "8d0ea73ce556f1eb460c91e8fe5fb0d09eeac59fa26b9162b0012c706d5ebcf9.mp3",
    "marin:Your turn — run the numbers.": "842290f2c58d5fac750f5229163c038a95ebda1bcb235e7d90a02f79ca78ad1b.mp3",
    "onyx:Case opened. Every cell is a building full of specialized rooms — first, let's find who guards the records.": "06396d0a467b14017a2e3ab2263da5af08597180b752fb8f0bdcd61c879109ca.mp3",
    "onyx:Cells are always building new proteins to grow and repair. Where does that assembly happen?": "4f4a109a178e4690a8c04053a1a473a0749297f9d663f9bb2962b737b3463c10.mp3",
    "onyx:Close, detective. Mitochondria make much ATP; nuclei store DNA; ribosomes assemble proteins.": "00a2aa152bb7574c4d0cc9990b92858c20f4eecb738bccd4b42923d8ca2d9aef.mp3",
    "onyx:Close, detective. Mitochondria produce much of the ATP during cellular respiration; the nucleus stores DNA and the membrane controls movement in and out.": "6261f8a551c734625f82405003cd735ca3e2bcb2bdebebfa5619bb3a7d3e50e9.mp3",
    "onyx:Close, detective. Ribosomes assemble proteins. The nucleus stores DNA, and mitochondria specialize in ATP production.": "2f74e7fab7899b2b8277400869b938b4475e1bab7a09a4e90da4b9eb6dc84981.mp3",
    "onyx:Close, detective. The nucleus stores DNA, mitochondria make much ATP, and ribosomes assemble proteins.": "c6387e982692beb6c6e3ea1e5b26105ba01527e4c1fff64d59ef3fe2f8fbfdf9.mp3",
    "onyx:Close, detective. The nucleus stores most DNA. Ribosomes assemble proteins and mitochondria help make ATP.": "c5cac208bdbb61a12af2a62dc9055ec0ac8c91afb8ac93ae17d5f33557f32adb.mp3",
    "onyx:Every cell carries a full instruction manual for the whole body. Where does it keep that manual safe?": "8476ad6991ebbbbcff4fd9e22ae501b4593406c4431744aaa867e6d84a0869da.mp3",
    "onyx:Follow the power trail and name its source.": "9114605bf29dfc2b558428d5afc6d5e03bbd3ec7dc018bcf32ce5a6155d200d7.mp3",
    "onyx:Here's where it all clicks into place.": "247e609e88ed2afaa375374f10c034a3119298ce58c4cf1a593210fb2591818a.mp3",
    "onyx:It is the cell's protected filing room for the instruction manual.": "fc0d278c881e6307f2c430bf7617c4b1b13279a35090a98f52b57dc2a41ecec4.mp3",
    "onyx:Last one — the whole picture in a single answer.": "783281c36322780aee00c9cbfab7cd6538f8c6cdeae06149edd577a0a5d23fde.mp3",
    "onyx:MITOCHONDRIA = ATP.": "b8e52df06a5e76f1e04b12f8e79281a446af9a3cf3b6a8fcf576557c19d705ce.mp3",
    "onyx:Mitochondria make much of a cell's ATP during cellular respiration.": "6e3cdba525f338f831b65ef84161c8e85675c8f3185355fdf31c201ada68f099.mp3",
    "onyx:Mitochondria supply much ATP; they are not the DNA archive or protein assembly line.": "cfd939762fc581276c6d29f7173a4981b6c0e5a3b9d2aecbf56ea1f40208b877.mp3",
    "onyx:Moving, thinking, breathing — all of it needs energy nonstop. Which cell part keeps supplying it?": "0eceecb95fca736cd49e4a83dfd902b56bc4770dd2948c93382b2dfe83a88c4a.mp3",
    "onyx:NUCLEUS = DNA instructions.": "3c0d0fdd4125dcf0da9eb84862c8b5d271252b73c1b23b0f246a1f24d25f46df.mp3",
    "onyx:Next: The Protein Shipment Mystery.": "e78295987af226dd5832d00e5752ce86a38a1de8b4bf3095ed5bc56e415263cc.mp3",
    "onyx:One room keeps churning out product day and night. Time to name the workshop.": "903013a7e184054816baaaf6afb8c6eb92017c42f9977ef2da4f9936c6dbd529.mp3",
    "onyx:One suspect left — identify the builder.": "16e15ee7ea6b72198c430cb9f4bf62a7a8e75bf10259c1596945818cdb71f3c6.mp3",
    "onyx:RIBOSOMES = proteins.": "98eb3b7052212df3b2fc99221d5895d7887e3bd9309e33e05a35b5e361eddd95.mp3",
    "onyx:Ribosomes assemble proteins by linking amino acids together.": "1f3a423bb2ffd43b3620e27ac544f1d16a9b5df51654833912b4f91039c461aa.mp3",
    "onyx:Ribosomes build proteins; they do not store DNA or specialize in ATP production.": "29545a0a6799c67072c4060cec2358cc9a37b9e1344db16ccea1511d026d1635.mp3",
    "onyx:The lights are on all over this cell. Something is generating the power, and we're going to follow it.": "684afa970bfaffeab0af29c67ece9b05ca93a3abedb57e7293f831478770dd12.mp3",
    "onyx:The nucleus stores instructions; it does not assemble proteins or make most ATP.": "d7e64eb0b37bb567c55681467df27a99471011aabfc59250e8f98bd75da74561.mp3",
    "onyx:The nucleus stores most of a eukaryotic cell's DNA instructions.": "595083a71736383a15381e41f4bed5dfba98ee4d7a72f4fc49816262d86de6b7.mp3",
    "onyx:They are energy stations that recharge many small ATP batteries.": "f5cb4ebb58a36ebf422638616a4db5a0d8399abb7dd9d421ef629b55af03fdce.mp3",
    "onyx:They are tiny workbenches that follow instructions to build a protein.": "82bc33ab03148652cc0fed66db9cbdff46b673908f9a26667832cecf9e2e2ca9.mp3",
    "onyx:Your move, detective — find who guards the files.": "2285fa3fc0563ca14f4d4bf819b531048648bacbf63d00324e672ff9bae3b6bb.mp3",
    "sage:A cold glass 'sweats' on a warm day, though nothing spilled. Where do those drops come from?": "8ae6cc9c6598b7e153eac027caa2147777ef3eda5a7761bb350294310c53d338.mp3",
    "sage:A little puddle sat in the sun this morning. By lunchtime it was gone. Where did it go?": "03dda1f193c5d38af73d4d2f7087832783e6752fea9efdc43c677ea68cc5db5a.mp3",
    "sage:A rain puddle vanishes on a sunny afternoon. Where did all that water actually go?": "0772317fb49177bbb1119acc4aa1a1685de0740f4aa0f48c6e8c570790d27cd4.mp3",
    "sage:CONDENSATION: gas → liquid.": "20c087f75e8ed829f594aae972f03920a8a68836bea010836ddbe7c00ba822cc.mp3",
    "sage:Clouds drift for days, then all at once it pours. What finally sends the water down?": "72ce1684f57d69cfc3e00fa1f61d8ed326e975bb546fad21daeb1a992891d070.mp3",
    "sage:Condensation is water vapor cooling and changing into liquid droplets.": "754377d748572c2545741a984c4dfe38cb48225bd68fbf835766e0b07c7781a5.mp3",
    "sage:Condensation makes droplets; evaporation makes vapor.": "f83d7f018fddc3ff91e2cc5985ae3c0c5183df42d2b1140e9b3aa881f47403b2.mp3",
    "sage:EVAPORATION: liquid → gas.": "6a38163fb338f0a93696ff22910459cebb9150ceff1d73130dca61dea15a68fa.mp3",
    "sage:Evaporation is liquid water changing into water vapor, a gas.": "65bc2ac0f8c2f295ef990f664758b129c61dc42f4a8bf7369f5178a615efca6f.mp3",
    "sage:Evaporation rises into air; it does not turn water into ice or rain.": "3eacf0cff8c8f04896082cc42a61194464bfbee8eb3670603d015f16770ff300.mp3",
    "sage:Here's where it all clicks into place.": "b8ea8ae0b37ae7db78e2030a6245588c65a0b3a061bd4becb311152207238eee.mp3",
    "sage:Last little step — name what's coming down from the cloud.": "d2f337f362d9b1acd2e5982beb36f6aaead73c94a68cab1c89ee347038be8a51.mp3",
    "sage:Last one — the whole picture in a single answer.": "b23f124fa1a4e41d1211670edcc4b06fe6ebed912a27b9baa375cdc88f79cf08.mp3",
    "sage:Like breath making tiny drops on a cold window, cooling vapor gathers into droplets.": "9be71c06638b8bf027aa398cc2b741b8289356143f68799596d3eef679a85765.mp3",
    "sage:Next: The Rainy-Day Garden Parade.": "58aa3b93fb5a6969be2ceaeb755e6fb621d3417a1ed2ea3a75350eb6a2386a1f.mp3",
    "sage:PRECIPITATION = water falls.": "5f971d10b2a220d0a63a4f14ab271e836fd5a61e2a4712f9920c36fa5fe53644.mp3",
    "sage:Peek up at the cloud and tell me what's forming.": "94f421a58a50b36bedfbab3efa7b6d0f435aa91549c37e9529888746f7f5669e.mp3",
    "sage:Precipitation falls; evaporation rises and condensation gathers cloud droplets.": "9c2ee692ab47c5a36a0f6d8cd24e35047a9e0eb9584fadee0c5b9b7cfdefb9e6.mp3",
    "sage:Precipitation is water falling from clouds as rain, snow, sleet, or hail.": "dc3b2ad7d8d6a6f5a4cdfa7ba900263769637b63f95fe21d5754d7ca7a505e51.mp3",
    "sage:So close, little sprout. Condensation turns cooling water vapor into tiny liquid droplets that can form clouds.": "a1417e7731c447b0a8ae2d7bf115bb05bb7c445424e84cfd4fa73711a82a1b9d.mp3",
    "sage:So close, little sprout. Evaporation changes liquid water into water vapor, a gas. It does not make ice or rock.": "9fc659ef7a3b320c5f1d963f17c1c94ebc029a8a777cc36fc4f5340772c17a84.mp3",
    "sage:So close, little sprout. Precipitation is water that falls from clouds. Evaporation rises, and condensation gathers droplets.": "226d3a290af3fdb5064bb057bc85409f80baadcd2e28290171fc53cf5d4cfca1.mp3",
    "sage:So close, little sprout. Warm water evaporates, vapor condenses into clouds, and water falls as precipitation.": "b9758c47aabda36d59c764f9371bca5726f4ee48b5c07a69979746017d05e8e0.mp3",
    "sage:So close, little sprout. Water can evaporate, condense into cloud droplets, and fall as precipitation before collecting again.": "eeeecdd7fee10bc449136be84059afbdaa384b20d22d4cd98dfe3df0fe203316.mp3",
    "sage:Sun-warmed puddle water can slip into the air one invisible molecule at a time.": "c97f746173955d8d6f95392238bf537d371488dd6f604564d59bffea20ef082f.mp3",
    "sage:The cloud is full and heavy now. Guess what happens next!": "bef321727200c5257c65fd636b32c0cf183f7346f4db11ee6ba859b3da1eace2.mp3",
    "sage:Way up high, the sky is turning cloudy. Let's peek at how a cloud is born.": "d648a46ea9b58d7d1259c46328f4dd726e674d16dd35b77934ba32add5b2a52e.mp3",
    "sage:When cloud droplets grow too heavy to stay aloft, gravity brings them back down.": "ad2db533724bb35cfee9f2483f197ef011c6ce6629c5c9950c94be2279cf27e0.mp3",
    "sage:Your turn, little sprout — follow where the puddle went.": "a7cce08fef6c026a0e8a544bdd5521c411a124185cc6901fee0b9ef255344337.mp3"
  }
}
